<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transport Select Committee – Inquiry into Winter Resilience in Transport</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written Evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Department for Transport (WRT 012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How resilient are the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s transport networks (including road, rail and air) to adverse winter weather?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What lessons have been learned since the severe weather experienced in the winter of 2009-10?  What practical changes have been made to ensure the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is now better equipped to deal with severe weather?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How well prepared are the Government, local authoriti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es and transport providers for adverse winter weather?  What more should be done to ensure a co-ordinated response?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> exceptional wintry conditions of the type experienced over the last few years would put any transport system to the test and lead to significant transport disruption.  It is therefore essential that after every period of severe weather, we carry out a tho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rough review to learn lessons, so that we are better prepared in future.  The Department for Transport welcomes the Inquiry by the Transport Select Committee as part of this process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since 2010 the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport response to severe winter wea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ther has significa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntly improved, following implementation of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecommendations arising from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">previous reviews. This means that as we head into the 2013/14 winter season this country is much better prepared than was the case in 2008/09 and 2009/10.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, it should be re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cognised that severe winter weather can be challenging for any transport network, even in those countries where such weather is common (as was reflected across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Northern Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> last year). The Department for Transport continues to work closely wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th all key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport operators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to ensure they are well prepared for each winter season</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> so that in the event of any extreme weather </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disruption to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the transport network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is minimised.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Roads</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Due to the problems on the highway network over the last few years, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particularly 2009-10 and 2010-11 winters, there have been a number of winter resilience reviews undertaken</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. These reviews identified lessons to be learnt and made key recommendations for both the Department for Transport and other transport operators. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Department for Transport has implemented all of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommendat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ions arising from these reports.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he RAC Foundation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">published an assessment of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how the country’s road network fared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">during the 2012-2013 winter period, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and also looked at whether les</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sons had been learnt since 2010. The report</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> noted that local highway authorities were continuing to maintain their level of spending on winter resilience and it also highlighted that there was evidence of cooperation between adjacent and intertwined count</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y, district and parish councils. The RAC Foundation suggested that this activity was underpinned by improved consultation with local communities and better communications with the media and the public.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Road Salt</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Lessons have been learnt since 2010 with r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">espect of road salt and supply. The Department continues to take action on road salt issues to ensure that the risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of a shortage in supply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">minimised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Actions taken include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(a) retaining a national strategic salt reserve of 425,000 tonnes and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensuring that we have robust distribution procedures in place</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(b) publishing an updated note on the Department for Transport website (at end of each October) which provides local highway authorities with details on how to access the strategic salt stockpi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le if it is required; and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(c) continuing to monitor salt stocks of highway authorities across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hold.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For local roads, which make up approximately 98% of England’s highway network, a local authority has a duty under Section 41 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the Highways Act 1980 “to ensure, so far as is reasonably practicable, that safe passage along a highway is not endangered by snow or ice”. Central Government has no powers to intervene in these matters in relation to local authority roads. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Winter ser</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vice planning and de-icing stock supplies are thus the responsibility of the respective highway authorities. The Department works closely with local highway authorities to ensure any resilience risks are identified early. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> also in regular contact with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Local Government Association in respect of road salt supplies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department has recently completed its annual Road Salt Restocking Survey of all local highway authorities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The results suggest local highway authorities are well underway i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n restocking salt supplies and our early analysis suggests that as a country we will enter the winter season with a good supply. This indicates that authorities continue to place orders with domestic salt suppliers and are receiving salt stocks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the salt supply chain is in a much better position than it was a few years ago. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We expect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">each local authority to have a current and robust winter service plan in place and the results from our recent survey suggest the majority have such a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">plan in place. We also encourage local authorities to make sure that they have appropriate communication channels in place to inform their local communities, including residents, businesses and other key representatives of their plans and gritting routes e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tc. The Department wrote to local authority leaders in August this year to stress the importance of early preparations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK Roads Liaison Group in conjunction with UK Roads Board and National Winter Service Research Group recently published updated gui</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dance on winter service as part of Well Maintained Highways Code of Practice. This builds on the work that was undertaken in 2011 and provides practical advice to highway authorities on issues such as salt spreading.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department also continues to make the public and other organisations, including local authorities, aware of the Snow Code which was published in October 2010. The Code reassures the public that if they use a common-sense approach and want to show commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nity spirit in clearing snow and ice from the front of their houses, pavements and other public spaces, they can do so in a safe manner without fear of legal action. The Snow Code is available on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Get Ready for Winter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ebsite.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department has also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reviewed its own internal procedures in respect of road salt following the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">winter of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2010-11. This included a review of its exposure to risks associated with the management of the national strategic salt stockpile. This work noted that the Department’s sy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stems of corporate governance, risk management and internal control arrangements were now well established and effective.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Rail</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Significant improvements have been made to the resilience of the rail network, following the problems faced in the winter of 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">09-10, which take on board the recommendations from various independent winter resilience reports.  More recent weather events have also highlighted the risks from storms and flooding, as well as from snow and ice.  The rail industry has generally dealt ef</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fectively with the weather events over the last year or so, although the industry must not become complacent.  When there are extreme weather conditions beyond the practical operating limits of the railway, some disruption to normal services is inevitable;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the issue is then about how best the railway can manage the situation so that those passengers who still need to travel can get to their destination safely. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The rail industry has improved its procedures for preparing for winter weather, and made signifi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cant investment in measures to keep the track clear, and to prevent equipment on the track and trains freezing up.  In 2011-12, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Department provided £16m funding for additional third rail heating across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sussex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wessex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> routes as part of a £3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8m programme of investment by Network Rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(NR) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to improve resilience of the network. Additional steps taken subsequently by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the train operating companies to improve winter resilience have included</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he overhaul and enhancement of equipment on trac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">k, trains and signals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he provision of specialised trains for snow and ice treatment and clearance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mprovements to the implementation of contingency timetables. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The industry has also implemented a comprehensive programme of actions to improve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">passenger information during disruption.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will take delivery of 3 new Rail Head Treatment trains in November and a further 3 next year t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o boost the existing fleet. These </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trains can provide treatment in both autumn and winter modes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the much longer t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erm, there may be a case for converting the third rail system to overhead electrification, which would also improve winter resilience.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s strategic business plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which is in line with the Government’s Investment in Rail Programme, includes plans for th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e conversion of the Southampton to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Basingstoke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> route, which will help test the business case for a more comprehensive conversion scheme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should be better equipped to deal with severe weather of all natures in the future due to their development of a 5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">year weather programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">immediate aim is to improve performance in adverse (as distinct from extreme) weather, with the longer-term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intention </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of providing an all-weather railway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Various initiatives including earthworks remote monitoring, customer comm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unications, drainage, and installation of weather stations are examples of what is planned going forward.  NR’s closer alignment with weather organisations should enable the industry to be better informed and prepared when they make weather decisions in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e future (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e.g. deployment of d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e-icer trains / snow removing trains etc).  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NR’s Strategic Business Plan foreshadowed high level measures to increase their expenditure in ‘Civils’ (structures, earthworks) including improvements to flood mitigation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ice of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egulation (ORR)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> draft determination confirms the need for NR to improve resilience, either by improving flood protection (where economic to do so) or enabling speedy recovery of operations after a flood (where protection is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not economic). ORR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> now considering the responses to their consultation before providing the ‘final’ determination</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which will outline the level of funding and delivery obligations on NR over the next 5 years.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As noted above, flooding has become a growing problem in recen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t years, especially on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Western Route</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> making good progress in identifying key locations on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Western Route</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where flooding resilience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs to be significantly improved. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NR has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> identified a number of projects which are vital to ensuring resi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lience in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Western Route</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is enhanced. These works could be delivered in phases from 2013-2016, subject to decisions on funding.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The rail network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emain vulnerable to unforeseen and/or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prolonged extreme conditions which are beyond the capability of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">current and planned mitigation measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Winter-proofing the network to, say, Scandinavian standards would be extremely difficult and expensive, and unlikely to demonstrate value for money.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Aviation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is the responsibility of individual airport operators and airlines to manage their infrastructure and develop resilience strategies to respond to specific severe weather events, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provide necessary additional investment in winter resilien</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ce</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT considers that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s airports and airlines have significantly improved their resilience to severe weather following the disruptions experienced during the winters of 2009-2012.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The busiest airports, Heathrow and Gatwick, have invested in new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and larger fleets of snow clearance and de-icing vehicle fleets, and have revised their operational command and control procedures to improve their response to severe weather, including working in closer co-operation with airlines and other transport provi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Passenger welfare arrangements have also been improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Other airports around the country have similarly revised and updated their operational response procedures.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Airports have improved their outward-facing communications by making greater use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their websites and social media vehicles to provide air passengers with as much notice as possible of service disruptions and flight cancellations, and have encouraged air passengers to contact their airline for up-to-date information. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Airlines have also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> improved their responses to severe weather, including through revised response procedures in co-operation with airport operators, better information and on-airport services for passengers (including assistance with their travel arrangements and, if necess</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ary, overnight accommodation), and improved airframe de-icer supply resilience.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a result of these improvements the aviation sector performed well over the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012-2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">winter period, although disruption occurred at a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> airports during the per</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iod 18-21 January 2013, when significant snowfall and prolonged freezing temperatures affected much of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2011 the CAA was asked to chair an Airport Performance Facilitation Group (APFG) to oversee implementation by industry of recommendations by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the South East Airports Taskforce.  The APFG shared best practice among </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">airports on better serving air passengers, particularly at times of disruption, through better anticipation and a more co-ordinated response between the various service providers at th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e airport. The work of the APFG concluded at the end of 2012 and further progress on the issues raised is being made in the context of the CAA’s work on consumer policy, new airport licences, and information powers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Civil Aviation Act 2012 received Ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">yal Assent in December 2012, and allows the Civil Aviation Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (CAA) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to include operational resilience conditions within airport operators’ licences, which could place appropriate obligations on airport operators to prepare for adverse weather and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ompel them to develop resilience strategies in conjunction with all service providers at the airport.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From 6 April 2013 new powers granted under the Act have applied to those airport operators not currently designated for regulation.  For those operator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s deemed to have substantial market power (currently Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted) the new powers will apply from 1 April 2014.  This is so as not to disturb the current price control period due to expire on 31 March 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> these improvements it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is likely that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s busiest airports could still experience some measure of operational disruption during future severe weather events. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Heathrow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> operates at almost 100% of permitted capacity every day of the week, so any disruption to operations is ver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y likely to lead to flight delays and/or cancellatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ns. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was not alone in experiencing disruption during </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the period </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">18-21 January 2013.  The snowfall and prolonged freezing temperatures covered much of Northern and Eastern Europe, and led to significant disruptions to operations at European airports including Paris Charles de Gaulle and Orly (40% of flights cancelled on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 20 January), Frankfurt (294 flights cancelled on 20 January), Brussels, Amsterdam Schiphol (60 flights cancelled).  By comparison, at Heathrow 328 flights were cancelled on 20 January – 27% of the programmed total.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disruption was also experienced at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Geneva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Basle and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Zurich</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> airports – airports generally considered more accustomed to dealing with severe winter weather impacts.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has an ongoing programme of engagement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with airp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ort operators, airlines, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CAA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and civil contingencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">experts from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ross Government on strategic resilience matters affecting aviation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including winter weather</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> maintains close working links with the aviation industry to lay the ground for effective communication during periods of disruption and to monitor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">progress with the industry’s resilience improvement programmes.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transport Ministers have made clear publicly that they expect airport operators and airlines to continue to learn lessons where problems did occur in January 2013, and to work cohesively to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ensure that the industry is as well-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prepared as possible for future severe weather episodes.  On 18 September DfT Ministers wrote to the operators of the largest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> airports, and to major airlines, seeking their assurances that they have implemented all n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecessary measures to respond effectively to any severe weather condit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ions this coming winter. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT officials respond pro-actively when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">weather-related aviation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incidents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">occur. A typical response includes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> liaising directly with industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for updates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, keepi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng Transport Ministers and the wider Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crisis response network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed, managing the public debate and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">facilitating links to surface transport pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oviders.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Maritime</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the event of severe weather threatening to disrupt English ports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iding objective is to work wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h those ports at risk (and their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">esilience partners in national and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to maintain operations so that critical supply chains connecting ports with their hinterlands are not interrupted. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The majority of our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ports are in exposed locations a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd can suffer from extremes of w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inter weather. In adverse conditions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> port operations will be temporarily disrupted but not stopped entirely. In extreme conditions which breach the port’s safety envelope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> operations will cea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se until the weather moderates but this is typically less than a day. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is important to remember that, in addition to snow, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">high winds and icing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> prevent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operation of key equipment such as cranes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although ports generally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">manage to overcome these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> operational difficulties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their continued operation is absolutely reliant on the ability of the road and rail networks to maintain effective links between ports and the hinterland. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to road clearance operations by local authorities, ports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to use considerable amounts of salt and de-icer themselves in order to maintain operations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In severe weather our ferry ports can only be as effective as allowed by the performance of their Continental partners.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In general, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">European ports appear to have l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ittle di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fficulty in coping with severe w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inter weather</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. There was an exception in France last winter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, where apparent co-ordination problems between the port of Calais, local authorities and the French rail operator SNCF presented challenges to English trans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">port operators who were trying to maintain international services. To mitigate this risk, DfT officials are working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to establish more effective links at official level between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and French</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> resilience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">leads.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since the severe w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inter of 2009/10 the Departme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt has issued detailed severe weathe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r guidance to ports each Autumn. It has held </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wash-up sessions with sector representatives, regional resilience teams and Departmental policy leads to examine performance and see what lessons can be learned to improve on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">severe weather performance. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over the past few years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Department has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">duced and circulated an annual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evere weather planning template </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to ensure consistency of approach across ports and aid development of a coherent and mutually supportive plan acr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oss the sector and government. This has received positive feedback from the industry.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Worked with the sector in strengthening their individual response drawing on the lessons learned. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Example measures include the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> purchase of more equipment like 4x4 vehicle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s, ploughs and spreaders to attach to existing equipment, increasing reserves of salt etc. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Worked with the sector to strengthen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">salt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">resupply arrangements and foster greater co-ordination at the local and regional level to ensure that prioritisation of salt supplies adequately reflects the needs of ports </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Took the lead in getting port authorities to establish stronger links with the reorganised Local Resilience Forums and local Authorities to ensure that they fully appreciate the priority attached to maintaining port operational capability and the potential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scale of that task in a large and complex port estate. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Assisted ferry ports in establishing robust lines of communication with port operators at the other end of their routes. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Regularly mounted exercises for key maritime staff to test our response to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">severe weather</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For their part ports feel they are on a continuing learning curve. With the support of the Department in issuing them with advice and guidance and hosting severe weather planning events their reaction to winter weather has improved steadily</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> since 2009/10.  Ports have increased salt reserves and strengthened resilience ties with local authorities and local resilience forums, and some are discussing the establishment of a strategic stockpile with local authorities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Major ports generally cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ider that they have now developed a robust severe weather programme but it is inevitable and necessary that lessons will continue to be learned and response improved year on year.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">These include the Independent Review of England’s Transport System in Winter (2010) and the Transport Select Committee Report, ‘Keeping the UK Moving: The Impact on Transport of the Winter Weather in December 2010’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">“Ploughing On – A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">review of highway resilience in Winter 2013”</span></p></body></html>